{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DTE7wpN2NqN75YcMDsAQxk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me read the test file to understand what tests already pass, and look at the current state of the file more carefully.\n\nThe improvement plan has 9 changes. Let me check what's already implemented in the current file:\n\n1. Change 1 (case normalization) - Looking at line 805: `return selected.map((s) => s.text).join(\" + \");` - No normalization applied. NOT implemented yet.\n\n2. Change 2 (Polish prepositions commonShort2) - Looking at lines 203-207:\n```\nconst commonShort2 = new Set([\n  \"a\", \"i\", \"of\", \"or\", \"to\", \"in\", \"on\", \"is\", \"it\", \"an\",\n\n\n```\nStill writing prepositions...\n```\n\nNow I'm checking which of the planned changes have actually made it into the code. Most of them haven't been implemented yet—the multi-line join protection, context-aware section label blocking, content-based garbage detection, parenthetical glosses stripping, position-aware dedup, and page number prefix stripping are all still missing. The only one that's already in place is the SEZON metadata pattern matching for season and category indicators.\n\nLooking at the unicode letters check in the garbled text detection, I can see it's already handling Polish characters properly, so that part of the Polish word fix is done. Now I need to go through the test file to understand what exactly needs to be implemented and then make those changes.\n\n```\n\ntypescript\nconst unicodeLetters = text.trim().replace(/[^a-zA-ZąćęłńóśźżĄĆĘŁŃÓŚŹŻ]/g, \"\");\n```\n\nThis is already filtering for Polish letters, so I can move forward with the remaining changes. Let me identify what's actually needed: case normalization for titles, expanding the Polish prepositions list, preventing multi-line content from being deduplicated, blocking joins on section labels, detecting garbage prologues based on content patterns, removing parenthetical glosses, implementing position-aware deduplication, and stripping page number prefixes. I'll work through these systematically in the title-extractor file. Add `ze`, `bo`, `na`, `ni`, `po`, `ku`, `od`, `za`, `co` to the set.\n\n### Change 3: Protect multi-line joins from component dedup\nAdd pre-dedup step to remove single-word component candidates when their join survived.\n\n### Change 4: Context-aware section label join blocking\nRelax section label join block to allow joins with ≥3 words.\n\n### Change 5: Content-based garbage prologue detection\nAdd `looksLikeCookingInstruction()` and update `findBurstEnd()` and `passesHardFilters()`.\n\n### Change 7: Strip parenthetical glosses\nAdd `stripParentheticalGloss()` and apply to candidates.\n\n### Change 8: Position-aware dedup\nAmend the dedup rule for position-0 compound titles.\n\n### Change 9: Page number prefix stripping\nAdd `stripPageNumber()` and apply before hard filters.\n\nNow I'm implementing these changes in the file, but I need to be careful about the substring deduplication logic—that block has to stay exactly as it is. Looking at Change 8, it asks me to amend the dedup rule, but the constraint says I can't modify that substring deduplication block, so I'm going to skip that particular change. I could handle this as a pre-deduplication step instead—removing the distant sub-header when there's a compound title at position 0, leaving the dedup block itself untouched. Looking at how the dedup logic works, it filters out candidates that contain shorter substrings, so for the HERB BAKED SALMON case, the full compound title would be removed because \"DILL SAUCE VARIATION\" is a shorter substring within it.\n\nAdding a protective filter before dedup...\n\nNow I should check how the existing tests perform with this change.\n\nActually, let me just go ahead and implement all the improvements I've outlined. I'll start by editing the file to add the new functions and update the existing ones in this order: the `normalizeCase` function, the cooking instruction detector, Polish prepositions to the garbled check, the instruction-prologue skip in `findBurstEnd`, the cooking instruction filter in `passesHardFilters`, and finally the parenthetical and page number strippers before `buildCandidates`.\n\nNow I need to handle the remaining updates to `buildCandidates` itself, add the join protection and compound protection before deduplication, and apply `normalizeCase` to the final output. Let me check the `isAllCaps` function to understand how it works for the case normalization...\n\nStill implementing the file changes... aces the first letter match only since there's no global flag. Let me verify the `isAllCaps` function works correctly across these test cases: \"BARSZCZ\" returns true, \"Barszcz\" returns false, and \"BIGOS MYŚLIWSKI\" also returns true even though the Ś character gets filtered out during the letter extraction. I'm realizing there might be an edge case where non-ASCII Polish characters aren't being counted properly in the all-caps check.\n\nFor something like \"ŻUREK\", the Ż gets removed by the regex since it only matches ASCII letters, leaving just \"UREK\" which is uppercase, so it still returns true. The normalizeCase function should handle the Polish lowercase letters correctly with its broader character set, so `żurek` would get the first letter capitalized properly.\n\nThis approach seems solid. Now I'm ready to implement these changes.\n\nI'm defining the normalizeCase function with a set of common lowercase words in Polish and English, then splitting the input text and capitalizing the first letter of each word except for those lowercase words that appear after the first position...\n\nExpanding the set of short common words to include more Polish prepositions and conjunctions...\n\nNow I'm adding logic to protect multi-line joins from being removed by their individual component words during deduplication. I'm filtering for joins that span multiple lines, then checking if enough of their component words exist as singles to warrant removal...\n\nRefining the 2-line join blocking to be context-aware—preventing joins when the first line is a section label and the combined result would be too short.\n\nNow I'm handling the 3-line join case with similar logic, checking if combining three consecutive lines would exceed the word threshold before allowing the join. I'm verifying the logic: the 3-word join \"Zupy Zimowe Warzywne\" wouldn't be blocked since it has 3 words, not ≤2, so it would proceed to the hard filters check. Now I need to confirm it actually passes those filters—checking if the individual words are valid and not garbled. of these are short lowercase words that aren't in `commonShort2`. The single-word check wouldn't apply since there are three words. But I need to verify the `isSectionLabel` check in `passesHardFilters` — it checks the entire normalized text against the set, not just the first word. So \"Zupy Zimowe Warzywne\" normalizes to \"zupy zimowe warzywne\", which isn't in SECTION_LABELS, so it passes the filter correctly.\n\nNow I'm working through the remaining changes: adding regex-based detection for cooking instructions that look like prologues, implementing a function to strip parenthetical glosses from recipe text, and applying that stripping during candidate generation so the filters evaluate cleaned text. I also need to make the position tracking aware of these transformations.\n\nBefore deduplication, I should add a step to remove distant sub-section headers that are substrings of compound titles at position zero. Then I'll add page number stripping and apply it during candidate building. I should check the existing tests to understand what's already working, then implement all these changes carefully while preserving the dedup logic itself, and run tests afterward to catch any breakage.\n\nNow I'm going through each edit systematically: adding the lowercase words constant and normalization function, introducing cooking instruction detection before the hard filters, updating those filters to check for cooking instructions, modifying the burst-finding logic to skip instruction prologues, refining the garbled text detection, and adding helper functions to strip parenthetical glosses and page numbers before building candidates. I also need to update the join logic in candidate building for the compound title improvements. I'm mapping out the exact line numbers for each function and code section so I can insert the new utilities in the right places and update the existing logic without breaking anything. Now I'll start making the edits systematically.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":23058,"cache_read_input_tokens":24832,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":23058},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b923ba25-2e78-4197-a1e6-b3c152deb8d9","uuid":"b28ec7b1-c608-486a-a7b3-cfcfea85d62c"}
