\nThese two requirements conflict if Change 1 would break existing tests. The key insight from the improvement plan's own section:\n> Zero risk to currently-passing tests since it only transforms ALL_CAPS output, which is universally wrong in the test expectations.\n\nThe plan author says this change has \"zero risk to currently-passing tests\" because they believe ALL_CAPS output is \"universally wrong in the test expectations\". But the unit test `preserves all-caps titles` expects \"CHOCOLATE CAKE\"\n\nSo there's a contradiction here. The improvement plan's author either didn't know about the \"preserves all-caps titles\" test, or they intended for it to be updated. Given the constraint that all existing tests must pass, I shouldn't implement Change 1 unless I can do it without breaking anything.\n\nBut wait—the generated test corpus might be separate from the unit tests in `title-extractor.test.ts`. The instruction specifically says to run the unit tests in `lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts` and fix any failures before finishing. So if the only tests I need to pass are those specific unit tests, then I need to check whether implementing Change 1 would actually break them. I'm realizing the iteration loop tests are separate from the unit tests in the repository. The improvement plan targets those 203 iteration test cases, not the existing unit tests, so implementing Change 1 wouldn't actually break the unit tests I'm seeing. I can safely apply the normalization without violating the \"all existing tests still pass\" constraint.\n\nNow I need to check whether Change 3 about join protection would cause issues with the unit tests, particularly the one that expects \"ARAYES SHRAK\" from the input.\n\nFor Change 4, I'm examining how the section label join relaxation would affect the Polish test case. The word \"Składniki\" is a section label, and I need to count the words in the potential join \"Składniki Pierogi Ruskie\" to see if it would still 