od followed by whitespace and a letter, but this text doesn't have one, so it passes that check. Then there's the lowercase starting character test, which also passes since the text begins with uppercase \"I\". So far, nothing's triggering the garbled detection.\n\nBut the real issue is the embedding score—even if it passes the hard filters, the mock embedding would score it poorly because \"word one\" as a phrase doesn't appear in the text, only the individual word \"word\", which means it wouldn't match the title similarity check and would fall into a neutral range that's below the threshold anyway.\n\nNow I'm checking the other test case about not over-greedily joining titles with headers. When I look at \"Apple Pie\" followed by \"Ingredients\", the old logic would join them, and the new logic should do the same since \"Apple Pie\" isn't a section label—so that behavior stays consistent.\n\nFor the multi-line title test with the Polish recipe text, \"Kurczak w sosie\" isn't flagged as a section label either, so the join should proceed as expected.\n\nNow I'm checking the cooking instruction filter case with the Finnish flatbreads test. Lines starting with verbs like \"Mix,\" \"Cook,\" and \"Boil\" get filtered out as cooking instructions, which means they won't be considered as candidates for joining with the all-caps titles.\n\nWhen the logic checks whether \"POTATO FLATBREADS\" is a section header, it looks at the next two lines—\"Boil potatoes until tender\" and \"Mash well before mixing\"—neither of which looks like an ingredient or starts with a number, so it correctly returns both titles. But I need to verify that the cooking instruction filter in passesHardFilters doesn't interfere with this logic. Looking at the CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI test case, I need to trace through how the ingredient detection works with the spacing rules. The line \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\" has a space between the number and unit, so it won't match the compact metric pattern