ck will kick in and skip them if they look like cooking instructions.\n\nI'm ready to implement these changes now. I'll include the commonShort2 update but skip the normalizeCase change since it would break existing tests, and I need to decide on the join modification.\n\nImplementing the stripParentheticalGloss function to clean up single-line candidates before checking filters...\n\nStill writing implementation... I see the parenthetical could come from two sources: either on the same OCR line as the title, or merged from a continuation line during the pre-merge step. For the continuation case, the merged result already contains the parenthetical, so applying the strip function to the single-line candidates should handle both scenarios since it operates on the final text content regardless of how it was assembled. I'm checking whether applying the strip operation before the hard filters would change which candidates get generated—for \"PIEROGI RUSKIE (Boiled Dumplings with Potato and Cheese)\", the full text passes the filters, but so does the stripped version \"PIEROGI RUSKIE\", so this approach should work consistently. Now I need to implement all these code changes.\n\nFor the parenthetical stripping function, I'm defining logic that checks whether to keep or remove the parenthetical part based on capitalization patterns—keeping it if the parenthetical is all caps (indicating a variation in the same language) or if both parts are mixed-case (suggesting both are title components), but stripping it when the base is all caps and the parenthetical is mixed-case, which signals a translation gloss.\n\nNow I'm tracing through the existing test case with continuation tokens to see how the function handles \"TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART\" after the lines are merged—the slash prefix means it gets combined, and I need to verify the stripping logic works correctly on this merged result.\n\nSimilarly, I'm checking the ampersand case where \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" gets pre-merged and then passed through the stripping function, confirming it stays unchanged since there are no parentheses.\n\nI'm satisfied the logic is sound, so I'm ready to implement the planned changes: expanding the short word list in the garbled detection function and adding a new helper to identify cooking instructions. I'm going through the edits systematically now, adding the join protection before the dedup block and then the position-0 compound protection to complete the changes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1594,"cache_read_input_tokens":58994,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1594},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b923ba25-2e78-4197-a1e6-b3c152deb8d9","uuid":"8532f90d-bf1d-4980-a2f7-d2fa542184c7"}
